Debriefing is short, because he gave succinct, clear answers - he paid attention and caught on to some aspects to the study relatively easily. He was suspicions of deception based on other studies he had done. During the experiment, again, I kept everything simple, short, and clear, with emphasis in the condition. This seemed to help, used follow-up question on "which condition" question. He was very expressive throughout the entire experiment - you can almost read his thoughts on his face.

He had a strong belief in the facial feedback hypothesis, expressed interest in clinical applications. Said he felt some change in emotions but kept the negative condition in mind. Debriefing was longer than others - longer, intuitive well-thought out, knowledgeable answers. In into, differentiated by saying "other experimenters," kept into short and succinct, emphasis on negative condition, told him to keep it in mind. This really seems to help.
